<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870929-0056 </DOCNO><HL> Business Brief:Lawter International Inc.</HL><DD> 09/29/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> LAWTENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM) </IN><TEXT>   Lawter International Inc., Northbrook, Ill., said it hired Morgan Stanley andamp; Co. to advise its directors on &quot;alternatives to enhance shareholder value,&quot; including the possible sale of the company.    Based on the current market price, the company has an indicated value of $366 million. Lawter, which makes chemicals used in producing ink, has about 18 million common shares outstanding.    In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange yesterday, the company's stock soared $4.75 to close at $20.375 a share.    Richard D. Nordman, president, said the advice from Morgan Stanley won't &quot;necessarily result in any specific event, but it could.&quot; He said that a leveraged buyout by management is one possibility that Morgan Stanley will consider, but he said that hasn't been proposed.    In the first six months, net income rose 26% to $7.7 million, or 44 cents a share, from a year earlier. Sales rose 6% to $53.5 million. </TEXT></DOC>